<HEAD>Half of Troops from Hurricane-Battered St. Croix Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half the 1,100
federal troops sent to maintain order on <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix</ORGANIZATION> after Hurricane
Hugo have returned home following a presidential order to withdraw.
   About 250 troops returned home aboard C-141 transport planes
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. On <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, the first 250 were flown back to the States,
said <ORGANIZATION>Joint Task Force</ORGANIZATION> spokesman Maj. <PERSON>Doug Foster</PERSON>.
   ``We should all be home for Thanksgiving,'' he said.
   The C-141 and C-130 transport planes were constantly flying in
and out of the island to evacuate heavy equipment and vehicles
brought by the soldiers when they arrived on <DATE>Sept. 21</DATE>, four days
after Hugo's ravaged the island.
   President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> ordered the withdrawal last week following a
request by Gov. <PERSON>Alexander Farrelly</PERSON>, who said the troops, most of
them from <LOCATION>Fort Hood</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Fort Bragg</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.C.</LOCATION>, were no longer
needed.
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> troops were sent to curb looting and help local
authorities maintain order. Most stores had already been sacked of
food and other commodities by the time the soldiers arrived.
   ``It's important for the <ORGANIZATION>Virgin Islands National Guard</ORGANIZATION> and the
police to get back on their own feet now,'' Foster said.
   Farrelly's request for the pullout was criticized by three
business organizations, the <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix Chamber of Commerce</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Board
of Realtors</ORGANIZATION> and a civic group called the <ORGANIZATION>United Concerned Citizens
of St. Croix</ORGANIZATION>.
   They charged the governor reneged on his promise to keep the
federal troops until all power and telephone services were restored.
   Hugo caused more than <MONEY>$500 million</MONEY> in damage to the <LOCATION>U.S. Virgin
Islands</LOCATION>, mostly on <LOCATION>St. Croix</LOCATION>, where most of the 52,000 residents
were left homeless.
</TEXT>
