<HEAD>FBI Arrests Man in Assassination of Chilean Ambassador</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th graf, `U.S. officials...', to ADD
comment from Sen. Kennedy. Picks up 5th graf, `A former...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive arrested in the <DATE>1976</DATE> car bombing
that killed the former Chilean ambassador was being held without
bond awaiting trial in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION>
   <PERSON>Jose Dionisio Suarez y Esquivel</PERSON>, 51, arrested at his <LOCATION>St.
Petersburg</LOCATION> home early <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, waived his rights to a bond
hearing before a federal magistrate here on charges of conspiracy
to murder a foreign official.
   Suarez is accused of providing the explosives and detonating
devices in the explosion that killed former Chilean Ambassador
<PERSON>Orlando Letelier</PERSON> and business colleague <PERSON>Ronni Moffitt</PERSON> as they drove
to work in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> on <DATE>Sept. 21, 1976</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials said they expect the new Chilean government to
prosecute top intelligence officials of the former military
government of Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> on charges of planning
Letelier's assassination, The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> reported today. The
killings long have been a sore point in relations between the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
   In <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Sen. Edward M. Kennedy</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Mass.</LOCATION>, welcomed the
arrest and commended the <ORGANIZATION>FBI</ORGANIZATION>, but said, ``Unfortunately, the
masterminds of this atrocity remain at large in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>. I hope and
expect that the new democratic government in that nation will do
all in its power to bring them to justice.''
   A former Chilean diplomat, <PERSON>Jose Miguel Barros</PERSON>, testified in a
Chilean court last year that <ORGANIZATION>Letelier</ORGANIZATION>'s assassination was ordered
by Chilean army Gen. <PERSON>Juan Manuel Contreras Sepulveda</PERSON>, who headed
the <ORGANIZATION>Chilean National Intelligence Agency</ORGANIZATION>.
   Pinochet stepped down as president last month after the election
of a civilian, <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> marhals said <PERSON>Suarez</PERSON> would be flown to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> as early
as <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. If convicted, he could face life in prison.
   <ORGANIZATION>FBI</ORGANIZATION> agents said <PERSON>Suarez</PERSON> had been leading a secretive, cautious
life in <LOCATION>St. Petersburg</LOCATION>, rarely even leaving the house.
   ``To our knowledge, he hasn't been employed in the <DATE>last 12</DATE> to 14
years,'' said Assistant <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON>Terry Furr</PERSON>.
   But his 30-year-old wife <PERSON>Elizabeth</PERSON> said <PERSON>Suarez</PERSON> worked at home as
an artist and never realized his face had been plastered in post
offices and courthouses around the country for more than a decade.
   ``No one ever notified him he was a fugitive,'' said <PERSON>Mrs.
Suarez</PERSON>, a hospital administration employee and mother of a
15-month-old boy. She said they have lived either in <LOCATION>Tampa</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>St.
Petersburg</LOCATION> throughout their nine-year marriage.
   Letelier served as Chilean ambassador to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> in
<DATE>1971-1973</DATE>, during the presidency of <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, who was
ousted by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> in a coup. Letelier had begun to emerge as a
leading international critic of <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> when he and <PERSON>Moffitt</PERSON> were
assassinated.
   <PERSON>Michael V. Townley</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> citizen who also was an employee of
the Chilean intelligence agency, was arrested in <DATE>April 1978</DATE>.
Townley was extradited to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, confessed to planting
the bomb on the order of superiors and spent 40 months in prison.
   According to the <ORGANIZATION>FBI</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Townley</PERSON>, <PERSON>Suarez</PERSON> and fugitive <PERSON>Virgilio
Pablo Paz</PERSON> built the bomb used in the assassination. Suarez
allegedly provided the explosives and detonators and purchased the
bomb parts.
   A federal grand jury also indicted three Chilean army personnel
in connection with the case.
   Maj. <PERSON>Armando Fernandez Larios</PERSON> pleaded guilty to being an
accessory after the fact to <ORGANIZATION>Letelier</ORGANIZATION>'s death and was sentenced to
22 months in custody. The <ORGANIZATION>Justice Department</ORGANIZATION> has failed to obtain
the extradition of two others.
</TEXT>
