<HEAD>Nationalists Claim Responsibility For Bombings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Police said...' to CORRECT location to southwest
of San Juan, sted northwest. Pickup 3rd pvs, `Similar explosions,..'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pipe bombs exploded <DATE>Monday</DATE> at a <ORGANIZATION>Bank
of Boston</ORGANIZATION> branch and a <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Army</ORGANIZATION> recruiting office prior to a <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>
hearing on the island's future political relationship with the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   Police said no one was injured and damage was slight in the
pre-dawn blasts in <LOCATION>Bayamon</LOCATION>, about 15 miles southwest of <LOCATION>San Juan</LOCATION>.
   Similar explosions, with no injuries and minor damage, occurred
<DATE>Friday</DATE> at a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Customs office in the southern city of <PERSON>Ponce</PERSON> and
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> at a Chase <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION> bank branch in the north-central city of
<LOCATION>Caguas</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Los Macheteros</LOCATION>, a militant pro-independence group that has been
relatively inactive in recent years, claimed responsibility for
<DATE>Monday</DATE>'s bombings.
   In a letter delivered to <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>San Juan</LOCATION>, the
group said it was protesting the ``farcical hearings'' being held by
a <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> committee here on a plebiscite planned for <DATE>1991</DATE> that will
allow Puerto Ricans to vote on their future relationship with the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   The group also cited the jailing of Macheteros members in
connection with the <MONEY>$7 million</MONEY> robbery of a <ORGANIZATION>Wells Fargo</ORGANIZATION> depot in
<LOCATION>Hartford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn.</LOCATION>, in <DATE>1983</DATE>.
   On <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, a federal court in <LOCATION>Hartford</LOCATION> sentenced a Macheteros
member, <PERSON>Juan Segarra Palmer</PERSON>, to 65 years in prison and fined him
<MONEY>$500,000</MONEY> for his part in the robbery. He and three other people were
convicted in <DATE>April</DATE>.
   Nine others accused of the robbery, including alleged Macheteros
leader <PERSON>Filiberto Ojeda Rios</PERSON>, are awaiting trial.
   The letter said the violence would continue until the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> ended its military, political and economic presence in <LOCATION>Puerto
Rico</LOCATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>FBI</ORGANIZATION> said it was investigating the letter, which bore the
star-and-machete logo of the <ORGANIZATION>Macheteros</ORGANIZATION>' ``Ejercito Popular
Boricua,'' or People's <ORGANIZATION>Army of Borinquen</ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION>Los Macheteros</LOCATION> is Spanish
for The Machete Wielders, and <ORGANIZATION>Borinquen</ORGANIZATION> is the Indian name for
<LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>.
   The explosions <DATE>Monday</DATE> occurred within an hour of each other, said
police spokeswoman <ORGANIZATION>Maria del Pilar Bon</ORGANIZATION>. She said one bomb slightly
damaged the bank building's facade and shattered windows of a nearby
bus terminal. The other blast shattered windows of the recruiting
office.
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee</ORGANIZATION> held
hearings in <LOCATION>San Juan</LOCATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE>, <DATE>Saturday</DATE> and <DATE>Monday</DATE> on the proposed
plebiscite on whether <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION> should remain a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> commonwealth,
become the 51st <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> state or seek independence.
   The <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> island of 3.2 million mostly Spanish-speaking
people has been a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> commonwealth since <DATE>1952</DATE>.
   It will be the first vote on <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>'s political status since
<DATE>1967</DATE>, when <PERCENT>67 percent</PERCENT> voted to remain a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> commonwealth, <PERCENT>32
percent</PERCENT> for statehood and less than <PERCENT>1 percent</PERCENT> for independence.
Puerto Rico's statehood and independence parties did not actively
participate in that vote.
   <PERSON>Sen. J. Bennett Johnston</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-La.</LOCATION>, who presided at the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>
hearings, said at the close of <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s session that the plebiscite
would be ``fundamentally different'' because the three status
options would be precisely defined and the vote would be binding on
<ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>.
   Under commonwealth, <LOCATION>Puerto Ricans</LOCATION> are <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> citizens and eligible
for federal benefits, but they cannot vote for president. The island
received <MONEY>$6.5 billion</MONEY> in federal money in <DATE>1988</DATE>.
   The committee's next round of hearings is scheduled for <DATE>July
12-14</DATE> to hear the <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> administration's views on the plebiscite.
President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> has said he favors statehood.
</TEXT>
