<HEAD>Chronology of Lebanon's Civil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION>'s
15-year-old civil war:
   
   <DATE>April 13, 1975</DATE> - Following political and sectarian rivalry that
has simmered since independence from <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> in <DATE>1943</DATE>, civil war
breaks out.
   <DATE>April 12, 1976</DATE> - <LOCATION>Syria</LOCATION>, alarmed at Palestinian-leftist gains,
sends in troops to support the Christians. The <ORGANIZATION>Arab League</ORGANIZATION> endorses
the move in <DATE>June</DATE> with a peacekeeping mandate.
   <DATE>July 1, 1978</DATE> - Syrian troops attack Christians in the worst
fighting in two years. At least 200 people are killed.
   <DATE>April 29, 1981</DATE> - <LOCATION>Syria</LOCATION> moves missiles into <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION> in response
to increased clashes with <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>, whose forces have intervened in
fighting between Syrians and Christians.
   <DATE>June 6, 1982</DATE> - <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION> invades <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION>, bombing Syrian missile
batteries and besieging Moslem west <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>, trapping the <ORGANIZATION>Palestine
Liberation Organization</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>Aug. 4, 1982</DATE> - <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> sends its Revolutionary Guards to <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION> to
fight the Israelis as they tighten their siege of west <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>. The
Iranian force reaches 3,000 men and trains Shiite Moslem fighters.
   <DATE>Aug. 30, 1982</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>PLO</ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON>Yasser Arafat</PERSON> and his guerrillas
evacuate <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION> under a truce plan supervised by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, French and
other forces, who withdraw <DATE>Sept. 10</DATE>.
   <DATE>Sept. 14, 1982</DATE> - President-elect <PERSON>Bashir Gemayel</PERSON>, a pro-Israeli
<PERSON>Maronite Catholic</PERSON>, is assassinated in a bombing. Israelis storm
into west <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>.
   <DATE>Sept. 16, 1982</DATE> - Christian militiamen massacre hundreds of
Palestinian civilians in <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>'s Shabra and <LOCATION>Chatilla</LOCATION> refugee
camps, an area under Israeli control. Lebanese leaders ask for
multinational peacekeepers to return and they are gradually drawn
into civil war.
   <DATE>April 18, 1983</DATE> - The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Embassy</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION> is hit by a Shiite
suicide bomber, killing 63.
   <DATE>Oct. 23, 1983</DATE> - Suicide truck bomb attacks by pro-Iranian
Shiites on <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and French bases kill 241 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> servicemen and 58
French paratroopers.
   <DATE>Feb. 6, 1984</DATE> - Moslem and leftist militias seize control of west
<LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>, forcing out Christian army units. Rival militias battle
each other. Hundreds of people are killed.
   <DATE>June 10, 1985</DATE> - The Israeli army completes its withdrawal from
<LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION>, but occupies a border strip patrolled by allied Christian
militiamen.
   <DATE>Feb. 22, 1987</DATE> - Syrian troops deploy in west <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION>, ending
three years of militia anarchy during which dozens of foreigners
are kidnapped.
   <DATE>Sept. 22, 1988</DATE> - President <PERSON>Amin Gemayel</PERSON>'s six-year term ends
with <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> unable to elect a successor. He appoints army
commander Gen. <PERSON>Michel Aoun</PERSON> interim prime minister. The Moslems
reject <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON> and remain loyal to acting prime minister <PERSON>Salim Hoss</PERSON>,
who governed under <ORGANIZATION>Gemayel</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>March 8, 1989</DATE> - <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON>, vowing to crush the militias, blockades
their illegal ports. Syrian-backed Moslems blockade the Christian
enclave, triggering six months of artillery battles that kill more
than 900 people. <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON> declares a ``war of liberation'' against
<LOCATION>Syria</LOCATION>.
   <DATE>Sept. 22, 1989</DATE> - An Arab League-brokered cease-fire takes hold
and <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION>'s lawmakers meet in <LOCATION>Taif</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION>, seeking a peace
settlement.
   <DATE>Oct. 24, 1989</DATE> - Legislators endorse the <ORGANIZATION>Arab League</ORGANIZATION> peace plan,
which cuts Maronite power and gives Moslems a greater say in
government.
   <DATE>Nov. 5, 1989</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> formally approves the Taif agreement.
   <DATE>Nov. 24, 1989</DATE> - <PERSON>Elias Hrawi</PERSON> is elected president to implement
the Taif accord. Aoun refuses to recognize <PERSON>Hrawi</PERSON> or the accord.
   <DATE>Jan. 30, 1990</DATE> - <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON> attacks the Lebanese Forces militia under
<PERSON>Samir Geagea</PERSON>, seeking control of the Christian enclave. More than
1,000 people, mostly civilians, are killed.
   <DATE>July 16</DATE> - Fighting erupts in <LOCATION>south Lebanon</LOCATION> between rival Shiite
militias. More than 200 are killed before a mid-August cease-fire.
   <DATE>Sept. 1</DATE> - Hrawi signs political reforms approved by <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION>
and warns that he'll move against <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON> if he continues his
defiance. Aoun rejects the reforms.
   <DATE>Sept. 30</DATE> - <PERSON>Hrawi</PERSON>'s predominantly Moslem army blockades <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON>'s
enclave.
   <DATE>Oct. 13</DATE> - Syrian and Lebanese government forces attack <PERSON>Aoun</PERSON>'s
enclave, forcing him to surrender and seek asylum in the <ORGANIZATION>French
Embassy</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
