<HEAD>St. Croix Residents Protest Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business owners and
residents of <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> protested President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s plan
to withdraw 1,100 federal troops that were sent to the island to
quell looting after Hurricane Hugo hit.
   The <ORGANIZATION>United Concerned Citizens of St. Croix</ORGANIZATION>, formed last week to
protest the plan, said it joined the <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix Chamber of Commerce</ORGANIZATION>
and the <ORGANIZATION>Board of Realtors</ORGANIZATION> to lobby the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION>
urging <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> to rescind the order.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Defense Department</ORGANIZATION> announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE> troops would all be
withdrawn within 20 days. The soldiers, mostly military police,
arrived <DATE>Sept. 21</DATE> to restore order, four days after Hugo had passed
and most stores were looted.
   In a full-page ad in the daily <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix Avis</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, the
group urged residents to phone the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION> to tell
authorities ``that we Crucians appreciate and want continued
military presence.''
   ``We have no electricity and telephones and we want to be safe
on the island,'' the ad said.
   The group, which represents shop owners and residents, said that
by <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> more than 300 calls had been made to the <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION>
and the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> pleading for the troops to stay.
   Chamber of <ORGANIZATION>Commerce President Jan Hanley</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> accused Gov.
<PERSON>Alexander Farrelly</PERSON> of reneging on his promise to not request the
troop withdrawal until power and telephones were restored.
   The <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix Board of Realtors</ORGANIZATION> in its annual meeting <DATE>Friday</DATE>
also denounced the withdrawal order and demanded the troops stay
until vital services are restored.
   A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>16th Brigade Batallion Command</ORGANIZATION>, one of the
units dispatched to <LOCATION>St. Croix</LOCATION>, said <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> that a small
contingent of the <ORGANIZATION>National Guard</ORGANIZATION> would arrive <DATE>Nov. 13</DATE> to replace
the federal troops.
   Hugo destroyed most homes and caused more than <MONEY>$500 million</MONEY> in
damage to <LOCATION>St. Croix</LOCATION>, an island of 50,000. It killed an estimated 56
people in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and 29 on the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> mainland.
</TEXT>
